<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Pluchea</i> <i>sericea</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Allenrolfea</i> <i>occidentalis</i>, <i>Atriplex</i> <i>canescens</i>, <i>Atriplex</i> <i>lentiformis</i>, <i>Atriplex</i> <i>torreyi</i>, <i>Baccharis</i> <i>salicifolia</i>, <i>Baccharis</i> <i>sergiloides</i>, <i>Salix</i> <i>exigua</i>, <i>Suaeda</i> <i>moquinii</i> and <i>Tamarix</i> spp. Emergent trees may be present at low cover, including <i>Populus</i> <i>fremontii</i>, <i>Populus</i> <i>trichocarpa</i> or <i>Prosopis</i> <i>glandulosa</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 5 m; canopy is intermittent to continuous. Herbaceous layer is sparse with seasonal annuals. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Pluchea sericea</i> ≥ 2% absolute cover; no other species with greater than or equal cover in the shrub canopy (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Around springs, seeps, irrigation ditches, canyon bottoms, stream borders, seasonally flooded washes. Soils are alluvial- or aeolian-derived sands or clay loams that are usually alkaline or saline. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Pluchea sericea</i> as a FACW plant. </div>
</div>

        
