    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ai-j). Stands occur at Carrizo Plain and in Cuyama Valley, where they associate with those of the <i>Atriplex lentiformis</i> and <i>Salix exigua</i> alliances.</li>
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Ca-d). Stands exist in Anza- Borrego Desert State Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b) and other areas scattered around alkaline springs, stream borders, and marshes.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ag, Ax-z). We know little about stands in this section, but they appear to occur sporadically in the southernmost subsections.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa-p). Stands are widespread at springs throughout the section. The often-photographed stands at Devil’s Cornfield in Death Valley National Park cover extensive flats with strongly alkaline crusts. Other stands exist in eastern subsections (Thomas et al. 2004), and stands typically associate with alkali sinks in both Death Valley and Saline Valley (Keeler-Wolf 2007b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Es). Stands occur along Canebrake Creek west of Walker Pass.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fd-e). Stands may occur in the southernmost subsections, but plot data are lacking.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba-e). Stands are common along margins of the Colorado River (Schoenherr and Burk 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fc-e). Stands with strongly alkaline crusts in Saline Valley cover extensive flats as open shrublands with wide, sparse patches of <i>Distichlis spicata.</i> Small stands occur at springs in the Grapevine Mountains as at Scotty’s Castle.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-c). Stands occur along the uppermost reach of the lower Santa Clara River drainage with <i>Arundo donax, Baccharis salicifolia,</i> and <i>S. exigua</i> (Stillwater Sciences and URS 2007), and they are increasing with disturbance in the upper Santa Clara River at the expense of willow, cottonwood, and sycamore alliances (Court et al. 2000). Stands occur in other subsections of this region on low-gradient slopes between 500 and 850 m (Calveg 2005).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands are typically small and reduced by a variety of disturbances including browsing by feral burros and cattle, ORV recreation, and ground water pumping. Planting <i>Pluchea sericea </i>effectively stabilizes and restores disturbed or degraded areas, though it tends to replace other plants once established (UCB 2006). Invasion by <i>Tamarix </i>is a concern, since it and <i>P. sericea </i>have similar water requirements (Cogan et al. 2004). </div>
</div>

    

    

